  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How should I start preparing for CLAT 2017?",
  "response": "Preparing for CLAT (Common Law Admission Test) 2017 requires a structured and disciplined approach. Here are some steps to help you get started:\n\n### 1. **Understand the Exam Pattern and Syllabus**\n   - **Sections**: The CLAT exam typically covers five main sections: English (including comprehension), General Knowledge and Current Affairs, Elementary Mathematics (Numerical Ability), Legal Aptitude, and Logical Reasoning.\n   - **Marking Scheme**: Each question carries one mark, and there is a negative marking of 0.25 marks for each wrong answer.\n   - **Total Questions and Duration**: The exam usually consists of 200 questions to be completed in 2 hours.\n\n### 2. **Create a Study Plan**\n   - **Daily Schedule**: Allocate specific hours each day for studying different sections. Ensure you have a balanced focus on all sections.\n   - **Weekly Goals**: Set weekly targets for completing topics and practicing mock tests.\n   - **Revision Time**: Dedicate time for revising topics you\u2019ve already covered.\n\n### 3. **Gather Study Material**\n   - **Books**: Refer to standard books for each section. Some recommended books include:\n     - **English**: 'Word Power Made Easy' by Norman Lewis, 'High School English Grammar and Composition' by Wren & Martin.\n     - **General Knowledge**: 'Manorama Yearbook', 'Lucent\u2019s General Knowledge'.\n     - **Mathematics**: 'Quantitative Aptitude' by R.S. Aggarwal.\n     - **Legal Aptitude**: 'Legal Aptitude and Legal Reasoning' by A.P. Bhardwaj.\n     - **Logical Reasoning**: 'A Modern Approach to Logical Reasoning' by R.S. Aggarwal.\n   - **Online Resources**: Utilize online resources, practice tests, and mobile apps for additional practice.\n\n### 4. **Focus on Each Section**\n   - **English**: Improve vocabulary, grammar, and reading comprehension. Practice reading passages and answering related questions.\n   - **General Knowledge and Current Affairs**: Stay updated with current events by reading newspapers, magazines, and watching news. Focus on important national and international events.\n   - **Mathematics**: Practice basic arithmetic, algebra, and geometry problems. Focus on speed and accuracy.\n   - **Legal Aptitude**: Understand basic legal principles and reasoning. Practice case-based questions.\n   - **Logical Reasoning**: Improve analytical and logical thinking. Practice puzzles, syllogisms, and logical sequences.\n\n### 5. **Practice Mock Tests**\n   - **Regular Mock Tests**: Take regular mock tests to assess your preparation level. Analyze your performance and identify weak areas.\n   - **Time Management**: Practice managing your time effectively during the mock tests to ensure you can complete the exam within the given time frame.\n\n### 6. **Stay Updated and Healthy**\n   - **Current Affairs**: Regularly update yourself on current affairs as this is a crucial part of the exam.\n   - **Health**: Maintain a healthy lifestyle. Ensure you get adequate sleep, exercise, and nutrition to keep your mind sharp.\n\n### 7. **Join a Coaching Class (Optional)**\n   - If you feel the need for structured guidance, consider joining a coaching class that offers CLAT preparation. This can provide you with expert guidance, study material, and regular mock tests.\n\n### 8. **Stay Consistent and Motivated**\n   - **Consistency**: Stick to your study plan and practice regularly.\n   - **Motivation**: Keep yourself motivated by setting small goals and rewarding yourself upon achieving them.\n\nBy following these steps and maintaining a disciplined approach, you can effectively prepare for CLAT 2017 and increase your chances of success. Good luck!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
